(SIGHS)

254
00:14:22,519 --> 00:14:26,284
If you are hungry,
go up and look around, Remy.

255
00:14:28,557 --> 00:14:30,616
Why do you wait and mope?

256
00:14:31,061 --> 00:14:35,326
Well, I've just lost my family,
all my friends,

257
00:14:36,499 --> 00:14:37,966
probably forever.

258
00:14:38,400 --> 00:14:41,130
- How do you know?
- Well, I...

259
00:14:41,804 --> 00:14:45,536
You are an illustration.
Why am I talking to you?

260
00:14:45,741 --> 00:14:50,441
Well, you just lost your family,
all your friends. You are lonely.

261
00:14:50,547 --> 00:14:52,741
Yeah. Well, you're dead.

262
00:14:52,849 --> 00:14:56,182
Ah, but that is no match
for wishful thinking.

263
00:14:56,286 --> 00:14:58,014
If you focus on what you've left behind,

264
00:14:58,120 --> 00:15:00,486
you'll never be able to see
what lies ahead.

265
00:15:00,590 --> 00:15:02,784
Now go up and look around.

266
00:15:16,972 --> 00:15:18,269
(SNIFFING)

267
00:15:21,411 --> 00:15:22,503
(SNIFFING)

268
00:15:25,815 --> 00:15:27,442
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

269
00:15:33,188 --> 00:15:34,553
Oh!

270
00:15:34,724 --> 00:15:36,715
(CHUCKLING)

271
00:15:38,662 --> 00:15:39,822
(CORK POPPING)

272
00:15:39,928 --> 00:15:41,088
WOMAN: Champagne!

273
00:15:41,197 --> 00:15:42,390
(PEOPLE EX CLAIMING)

274
00:15:42,499 --> 00:15:43,591
What are you doing?

275
00:15:43,700 --> 00:15:44,688
(SIGHING)

276
00:15:44,801 --> 00:15:45,927
I'm hungry.

277
00:15:46,135 --> 00:15:47,534
I don't know where I am,

278
00:15:47,636 --> 00:15:49,331
and I don't know
when I'll find food again.

279
00:15:49,438 --> 00:15:53,033
Remy, you are better than that.
You are a cook.

280
00:15:53,243 --> 00:15:58,145
A cook makes. A thief takes.
You are not a thief.

281
00:15:58,815 --> 00:16:00,475
But I am hungry.

282
00:16:00,582 --> 00:16:02,072
(CHUCKLES)

283
00:16:02,184 --> 00:16:03,846
Food will come, Remy.

284
00:16:03,952 --> 00:16:08,514
Food always comes
to those who love to cook.

285
00:16:15,164 --> 00:16:16,131
(SNIFFING)

286
00:16:20,602 --> 00:16:22,900
- You think I am playing?
- You don't have the guts.

287
00:16:23,005 --> 00:16:24,029
(GUNSHOT)

288
00:16:24,139 --> 00:16:25,697
(WOMAN EX CLAIMING)

289
00:16:37,921 --> 00:16:39,388
(BARKING)

290
00:17:10,319 --> 00:17:11,445
Paris?

291
00:17:12,055 --> 00:17:15,547
(CHUCKLING) All this time
I've been underneath Paris?

292
00:17:17,660 --> 00:17:18,854
Wow.

293
00:17:21,564 --> 00:17:23,259
It's beautiful.

294
00:17:24,467 --> 00:17:27,060
The most beautiful.

295
00:17:27,403 --> 00:17:29,997
Gusteau's? Your restaurant?

296
00:17:30,105 --> 00:17:32,539
You've led me to your restaurant.

297
00:17:33,609 --> 00:17:38,808
It seems as though I have. Yes.
There it is! I have led you to it!

298
00:17:38,914 --> 00:17:40,279
I got to see this.

299
00:17:40,950 --> 00:17:42,508
HORST: Ready to go on table seven.
COLETTE: Coming around.

300
00:17:42,618 --> 00:17:44,314
LALO: One order of steamed pike up.
MAN: Coming up.

301
00:17:44,420 --> 00:17:46,148
LAROUSSE: I need
more soup bowls, please.

302
00:17:46,256 --> 00:17:48,849
COLETTE: I need two rack of lamb.
I need more leeks.

303
00:17:48,958 --> 00:17:52,222
I need two salmon, three
salade composée, and three filet.

304
00:17:52,327 --> 00:17:54,228
LAROUSSE: Three orders
of salade composée working.

305
00:17:54,329 --> 00:17:56,025
Firing two orders, seared salmon.

306
00:17:56,132 --> 00:17:58,500
Three filet working. I need plates.

307
00:17:58,768 --> 00:18:01,430
HORST: Fire seven.
MAN: Three salade composée up.

308
00:18:01,538 --> 00:18:03,438
COLETTE: Don't mess with my mise!

309
00:18:03,673 --> 00:18:04,765
LAROUSSE: Open down low.

310
00:18:04,874 --> 00:18:07,808
MAN: I'm getting buried here.

311
00:18:07,977 --> 00:18:10,673
Hello, Chef Skinner.
How your night be now?

312
00:18:10,779 --> 00:18:12,805
HORST: Bonjour, chef.
LAROUSSE: Hello, Chef Skinner.

313
00:18:12,915 --> 00:18:15,406
- Evening, chef.
- WAITER: Ordering deux filet.

314
00:18:15,518 --> 00:18:17,383
Hey, boss, look who is here.

315
00:18:17,487 --> 00:18:19,886
Alfredo Linguini, Renata's little boy.

316
00:18:19,989 --> 00:18:21,615
- Hi.
- All grown up, eh?

317
00:18:21,723 --> 00:18:24,249
You remember Renata,
Gusteau's old flame?

318
00:18:24,359 --> 00:18:25,451
(CHUCKLING)

319
00:18:25,561 --> 00:18:28,690
- Yes. How are you...
- Linguini.

320
00:18:28,798 --> 00:18:32,996
Yes, Linguini. So nice of you to visit.
How is...

321
00:18:33,102 --> 00:18:34,932
- My mother?
- Renata.

322
00:18:35,038 --> 00:18:37,871
- Yes, Renata. How is she?
- Good.

323
00:18:38,173 --> 00:18:41,575
Well, not... She's been better. I mean...

324
00:18:41,677 --> 00:18:42,940
She died.

325
00:18:43,512 --> 00:18:44,707
Oh.

326
00:18:45,080 --> 00:18:46,240
I'm sorry.

327
00:18:46,348 --> 00:18:49,943
Oh, don't be. She believed in heaven,
so she's covered.

328
00:18:50,086 --> 00:18:52,576
You know, afterlife-wise?

329
00:18:58,461 --> 00:18:59,689
(TITTERS)

330
00:19:01,396 --> 00:19:04,490
- What's this?
- She left it for you.

331
00:19:04,733 --> 00:19:08,067
I think she hoped it would help me,

332
00:19:08,171 --> 00:19:10,570
you know, get a job here.

333
00:19:10,673 --> 00:19:13,335
But of course.
Gusteau wouldn't hesitate.

334
00:19:13,442 --> 00:19:14,500
Any son of Renata's is more than...

335
00:19:14,611 --> 00:19:18,240
Yes, well, we could file this
and if something suitable opens up...

336
00:19:18,347 --> 00:19:19,405
We have already hired him.

337
00:19:19,515 --> 00:19:23,246
What? How dare you hire someone
without my...

338
00:19:23,353 --> 00:19:25,082
We needed a garbage boy.

339
00:19:25,788 --> 00:19:28,188
Oh, garbage. Well...

340
00:19:28,391 --> 00:19:30,086
I'm glad it worked out.

341
00:19:33,363 --> 00:19:34,590
Uh...

342
00:19:36,732 --> 00:19:37,893
(GULPS)

343
00:19:39,868 --> 00:19:41,268
I can't believe it.

344
00:19:41,537 --> 00:19:44,700
A real gourmet kitchen,
and I get to watch.

345
00:19:44,941 --> 00:19:48,035
You've read my book.
Let us see how much you know, huh?

346
00:19:48,243 --> 00:19:49,801
Which one is the chef?

347
00:19:49,913 --> 00:19:51,778
Oh! Uh...

348
00:19:52,248 --> 00:19:54,579
- Oh, that guy.
- Very good.

349
00:19:54,817 --> 00:19:56,307
Who is next in command?

350
00:19:56,419 --> 00:19:59,217
The sous chef. There.

351
00:19:59,555 --> 00:20:03,457
The sous is responsible for the kitchen
when the chef's not around.

352
00:20:03,726 --> 00:20:07,058
Saucier, in charge of sauces.
Very important.

353
00:20:07,262 --> 00:20:11,358
Chef de partie, demi chef de partie,
both important.

354
00:20:11,467 --> 00:20:14,265
Commis, commis, they're cooks.
Very important.

355
00:20:14,470 --> 00:20:17,564
You are a clever rat. Now, who is that?

356
00:20:18,273 --> 00:20:20,401
Oh, him? He's nobody.

357
00:20:20,509 --> 00:20:22,568
Not nobody. He is part of the kitchen.

358
00:20:22,679 --> 00:20:24,544
No, he's a plongeur or something.

359
00:20:24,646 --> 00:20:27,137
He washes dishes or takes out
the garbage. He doesn't cook.

360
00:20:27,250 --> 00:20:30,480
- But he could.
- (SNICKERING) Uh, no.

361
00:20:30,586 --> 00:20:32,816
How do you know?
What do I always say?

362
00:20:32,922 --> 00:20:34,548
Anyone can cook.

363
00:20:34,656 --> 00:20:38,593
Well, yeah, anyone can.
That doesn't mean that anyone should.

364
00:20:38,694 --> 00:20:42,256
(CHUCKLING) Well,
that is not stopping him. See?

365
00:20:43,031 --> 00:20:47,662
What is he doing?
No. No! No, this is terrible!

366
00:20:47,769 --> 00:20:49,362
(STUTTERING)

367
00:20:49,471 --> 00:20:53,101
He's ruining the soup.
And nobody's noticing?

368
00:20:53,308 --> 00:20:55,209
It's your restaurant. Do something.

369
00:20:55,310 --> 00:20:58,473
What can I do?
I am a figment of your imagination.

370
00:20:58,580 --> 00:20:59,848
But he's ruining the soup!
We got to tell someone that he's...

371
00:20:59,848 --> 00:21:01,509
But he's ruining the soup!
We got to tell someone that he's...

372
00:21:07,423 --> 00:21:08,788
(GASPING)

373
00:21:08,891 --> 00:21:11,689
COLETTE: Table five coming up,
right now.

374
00:21:16,164 --> 00:21:17,461
(GASPS)

375
00:21:19,067 --> 00:21:20,865
LALO: Coming down the line.
COLETTE: Set.

376
00:21:22,438 --> 00:21:23,665
Ah!

377
00:21:29,979 --> 00:21:32,038
COLETTE: Hot! Open oven!

378
00:21:33,348 --> 00:21:34,680
(PANTING)

379
00:21:39,721 --> 00:21:41,052
Ah!

380
00:21:49,699 --> 00:21:51,290
HORST: Coming around.

381
00:22:07,282 --> 00:22:08,477
Ooh!

382
00:22:11,887 --> 00:22:15,324
COLETTE: Oui, chef.
One filet mignon, three lamb, two duck.

383
00:22:35,778 --> 00:22:38,372
HORST: Fire those soufflés
for table six, ja.

384
00:22:38,580 --> 00:22:40,515
- COLETTE: Five minutes, chef.
- Oh, God.

385
00:22:45,887 --> 00:22:48,288
Tonight,
I'd like to present the foie gras.

386
00:22:48,391 --> 00:22:49,857
It has a wonderful finish.

387
00:22:49,959 --> 00:22:51,256
- REMY: Ooh!
- Ah!

388
00:22:54,564 --> 00:22:55,530
Hmm.

389
00:23:05,007 --> 00:23:06,201
(GROANS)

390
00:23:09,311 --> 00:23:11,746
HORST: Ready to go on table seven.
Come on! Let's go!

391
00:23:11,847 --> 00:23:12,905
WAITER: Oui, chef.

392
00:23:17,886 --> 00:23:19,218
(VOMITING)

393
00:23:25,595 --> 00:23:26,856
(SNIFFING)

394
00:23:40,675 --> 00:23:42,165
(GRUNTING INDECISIVELY)

395
00:23:45,448 --> 00:23:46,938
(BUBBLING GENTLY)

396
00:23:54,656 --> 00:23:56,557
Remy! What are you waiting for?

397
00:23:56,659 --> 00:23:58,490
Is this going to become a regular thing
with you?

398
00:23:58,594 --> 00:24:01,256
You know how to fix it.
This is your chance.

399
00:24:03,432 --> 00:24:04,762
(BELL DINGS)

400
00:24:51,846 --> 00:24:53,144
(GASPS)

401
00:24:56,085 --> 00:25:00,545
The soup! Where is the soup?
Out of my way.

402
00:25:01,123 --> 00:25:03,250
Move it, garbage boy!

403
00:25:03,960 --> 00:25:06,519
You are cooking?

404
00:25:06,729 --> 00:25:10,164
How dare you cook in my kitchen?

405
00:25:10,266 --> 00:25:12,325
Where do you get the gall

406
00:25:12,434 --> 00:25:16,064
to even attempt something
so monumentally idiotic?

407
00:25:16,172 --> 00:25:18,163
I should have you drawn
and quartered!

408
00:25:18,273 --> 00:25:21,367
I'll do it. I think the law is on my side.

409
00:25:21,477 --> 00:25:22,443
(PLEADING)

410
00:25:22,545 --> 00:25:24,011
Larousse, draw and quarter this man

411
00:25:24,113 --> 00:25:29,278
after you put him in the duck press
to squeeze the fat out of his head.

412
00:25:29,384 --> 00:25:32,512
- What are you blathering about?
- (STUTTERING) The soup!

413
00:25:34,789 --> 00:25:36,086
Soup?

414
00:25:36,791 --> 00:25:38,452
Stop that soup!

415
00:25:38,661 --> 00:25:42,357
No!

416
00:25:42,597 --> 00:25:44,224
(PIANO PLAYING SOFTLY)

417
00:25:56,778 --> 00:25:57,871
Waiter.

418
00:25:58,047 --> 00:25:59,377
(EX CLAIMS)

419
00:25:59,481 --> 00:26:01,779
Linguini!

420
00:26:01,983 --> 00:26:03,473
You're fired!

421
00:26:03,685 --> 00:26:06,621
F-l-R-E-D! Fired!

422
00:26:06,721 --> 00:26:09,019
She wants to see the chef.

423
00:26:09,125 --> 00:26:11,218
(STUTTERING) But he...

424
00:26:12,662 --> 00:26:13,959
(CLEARING THROAT)

425
00:26:26,608 --> 00:26:30,477
- What did the customer say?
- It was not a customer. It was a critic.

426
00:26:30,578 --> 00:26:32,740
- Ego?
- Solene LeClaire.

427
00:26:32,847 --> 00:26:36,909
- LeClaire? What did she say?
- She likes the soup.

428
00:26:37,086 --> 00:26:38,712
- Wait.
- What do you mean, "Wait"?

429
00:26:38,820 --> 00:26:40,448
You're the reason I'm in this mess.

430
00:26:40,556 --> 00:26:41,921
(SHUSHING)
Someone is asking about your soup.

431
00:26:52,034 --> 00:26:54,627
What are you playing at?

432
00:26:54,737 --> 00:26:56,135
(STAMMERING)

433
00:26:57,038 --> 00:26:58,300
Am I still fired?

434
00:26:58,406 --> 00:27:00,534
- COLETTE: You can't fire him.
- What?

435
00:27:00,643 --> 00:27:03,942
LeClaire likes it, yeah?
She made a point of telling you so.

436
00:27:04,046 --> 00:27:05,343
If she write a review to that effect

437
00:27:05,448 --> 00:27:07,415
and find out you fired
the cook responsible...

438
00:27:07,516 --> 00:27:10,679
- (SCOFFS) He's a garbage boy.
- Who made something she liked.

439
00:27:10,786 --> 00:27:13,049
How can we claim to represent
the name of Gusteau

440
00:27:13,154 --> 00:27:15,316
if we don't uphold
his most cherished belief?

441
00:27:15,423 --> 00:27:18,290
And what belief is that,
Mademoiselle Tatou?

442
00:27:18,394 --> 00:27:19,383
Anyone can cook.

443
00:27:24,266 --> 00:27:29,965
Perhaps I have been a bit harsh
on our new garbage boy.

444
00:27:30,373 --> 00:27:32,636
He has taken a bold risk

445
00:27:32,741 --> 00:27:37,144
and we should reward that,
as Chef Gusteau would have.

446
00:27:37,512 --> 00:27:40,505
If he wishes
to swim in dangerous waters,

447
00:27:40,615 --> 00:27:42,105
who are we to deny him?

448
00:27:42,218 --> 00:27:43,241
(CLEARING THROAT)

449
00:27:43,352 --> 00:27:45,582
- You were escaping?
- Oh, yeah.

450
00:27:45,688 --> 00:27:49,852
Since you have expressed
such an interest in his cooking career,

451
00:27:49,959 --> 00:27:51,324
you shall be responsible for it.

452
00:27:51,426 --> 00:27:52,586
(TITTERING)

453
00:27:53,429 --> 00:27:54,862
Anyone else?

454
00:27:56,865 --> 00:27:58,730
Then back to work.

455
00:27:59,434 --> 00:28:02,961
You are either very lucky
or very unlucky.

456
00:28:03,204 --> 00:28:08,575
You will make the soup again,
and this time, I'll be paying attention.

457
00:28:08,844 --> 00:28:11,607
Very close attention.

458
00:28:11,913 --> 00:28:16,351
They think you might be a cook.
But you know what I think, Linguini?

459
00:28:16,585 --> 00:28:19,951
I think you are a sneaky,
overreaching little...

460
00:28:20,055 --> 00:28:21,113
(GASPS)

461
00:28:21,222 --> 00:28:22,451
Rat!

462
00:28:22,791 --> 00:28:24,019
(EX CLAIMING)

463
00:28:24,894 --> 00:28:26,384
- Rat!
- HORST: Get the rat.

464
00:28:26,595 --> 00:28:28,653
Linguini. Get something to trap it.

465
00:28:28,763 --> 00:28:30,355
HORST: It's getting away.
Get it, get it, get it.

466
00:28:31,066 --> 00:28:32,931
- What should I do now?
- Kill it.

467
00:28:33,035 --> 00:28:35,559
- Now?
- No, not in the kitchen. Are you mad?

468
00:28:35,738 --> 00:28:37,261
Do you know what would happen to us

469
00:28:37,373 --> 00:28:39,840
if anyone knew
we had a rat in our kitchen?

470
00:28:39,942 --> 00:28:41,568
They'd close us down.

471
00:28:41,676 --> 00:28:44,076
Our reputation is hanging by a thread
as it is.

472
00:28:44,180 --> 00:28:48,309
Take it away from here. Far away.
Kill it. Dispose of it. Go!

473
00:28:49,151 --> 00:28:50,584
Whoa!

474
00:28:54,222 --> 00:28:55,190
Doh!

475
00:29:16,077 --> 00:29:17,635
(REMY PANTING)

476
00:29:24,987 --> 00:29:28,820
Don't look at me like that!
You aren't the only one who's trapped.

477
00:29:28,923 --> 00:29:31,050
They expect me to cook it again!

478
00:29:31,292 --> 00:29:34,057
I mean, I'm not ambitious.
I wasn't trying to cook.

479
00:29:34,163 --> 00:29:36,289
I was just trying to stay out of trouble.

480
00:29:36,397 --> 00:29:39,423
You're the one who was getting fancy
with the spices!

481
00:29:39,535 --> 00:29:44,438
What did you throw in there? Oregano?
No? What? Rosemary?

482
00:29:44,707 --> 00:29:47,174
That's a spice, isn't it? Rosemary?

483
00:29:47,710 --> 00:29:50,177
You didn't throw rosemary in there?

484
00:29:50,512 --> 00:29:54,608
Then what was all the flipping
and all the throwing the...

485
00:29:55,851 --> 00:29:57,182
(SIGHING)

486
00:29:58,653 --> 00:30:02,055
I need this job. I've lost so many.

487
00:30:02,423 --> 00:30:06,519
I don't know how to cook, and now
I'm actually talking to a rat as if you...

488
00:30:06,628 --> 00:30:07,617
(GASPS)

489
00:30:07,730 --> 00:30:08,958
Did you nod?

490
00:30:09,064 --> 00:30:11,191
Have you been nodding?

491
00:30:12,667 --> 00:30:14,431
You understand me?

492
00:30:14,970 --> 00:30:16,631
So I'm not crazy!

493
00:30:17,839 --> 00:30:19,898
Wait a second, wait a second.

494
00:30:20,976 --> 00:30:23,672
I can't cook, can I?

495
00:30:25,681 --> 00:30:27,443
But you...

496
00:30:28,116 --> 00:30:30,914
You can, right?

497
00:30:32,153 --> 00:30:34,622
Look, don't be so modest.
You're a rat, for Pete's sake.

498
00:30:34,722 --> 00:30:37,123
Whatever you did, they liked it.

499
00:30:37,726 --> 00:30:40,286
Yeah. This could work.

500
00:30:41,130 --> 00:30:42,357
Hey, they liked the soup!

501
00:30:42,463 --> 00:30:43,760
(SCREAMING)

502
00:30:45,867 --> 00:30:50,931
They liked the soup.
Do you think you could do it again?

